      <div xml:id="NA310-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">1. itu vāyilākap pukka viṟaliyait tōḻi colliyatu.
            2. viṟaliyai yetirppaṭṭa parattai colliyatūumām.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. This is what the confidante said to the dancing girl who had entered as a mediator. 2. It is also what the other woman said who was confronted with the dancing girl.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA310">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            viḷakki ṉaṉṉa cuṭarviṭu tāmaraik</l>
<l>            kaḷiṟṟuccevi yaṉṉa pācaṭai tayaṅka</l>
<l>            vuṇṭuṟai makaḷi ririyak kuṇṭunīr</l>
<l>            vāḷai piṟaḻu mūraṟku nāḷai</l>
<l>            makaṭkoṭai yetirnta maṭaṅkeḻu peṇṭē</l>
<l>            tolainta nāvi ṉulainta kuṟumoḻi</l>
<l>            yuṭampaṭ ṭōrāyt tāyarō ṭoḻipuṭaṉ</l>
<l>            collalai kollō nīyē vallaik</l>
<l>            kaṉṟupeṟu valcip pāṇaṉ kaiyatai</l>
<l>            vaḷḷuyirt taṇṇumai pōla</l>
<l>            vuḷyātu millatōr pōrvaiyuñ collē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Foolish woman, opposed<note place="foot">Funnily, the interpretation of this poem depends on this one word <term xml:lang="ta">etirnta</term>, which obviously can mean both agreeing and disagreeing. If it is agreeing, then we can go along with the <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷavi</term> which makes this a poem addressed by the confidante to the <term xml:lang="ta">viṟali</term> as a matchmaker. If it is disagreeing, then it may well be a poem about a woman of the family (the neighbourhood) who does not want to give away the daughter, though it is clear that in the end everybody will have to consent.</note> to giving [your] daughter away</l>
<l rend="indent">tomorrow to the man from the village, where the Vāḷai fish are leaping</l>
<l rend="indent2">in the deep water so that the women retreat at the drinking[-water] ghat,</l>
<l rend="indent3">while lotus, emitting glow as a lamp,</l>
<l rend="indent3">[and] green leaves [big] as elephant’s ears are glittering,</l>
<l>won’t you speak [favourably] at once,</l>
<l rend="indent">staying behind with the mother, becoming one in agreement,</l>
<l rend="indent">with agitated short words from exhausted(?) tongues?</l>
<l>Just covering [is your] word that has nothing inside,</l>
<l rend="indent">as the sharp-toned Taṇṇumai drum,</l>
<l rend="indent">wonderful(?), in the hand of the bard with food in obtaining a calf,</l>
<l rend="indent">skilfully.<note place="foot">This line is profoundly unsatisfactory, for syntax as well as for content. What is the point of the comparison? The drum sounds warlike (or in any way powerful), but as soon as the bard’s stomach is fed, it will stop?</note></l>
        </lg>
      </div>
